WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.480
Hey everyone, my name is Cecil and I'm here with my colleague Jay and we're from the Posit

00:00:11.480 --> 00:00:20.879
Support team and we're going to show you how to connect your Workbench host to Active Directory.

00:00:20.879 --> 00:00:27.200
So connecting to Active Directory is mostly done through the command line and our documentation

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:35.040
has most of the steps to do so. There are variations depending on how your Active Directory is configured,

00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:42.080
but we're going to follow the standard way in our Workbench documentation with connecting Ubuntu 24

00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:52.000
to our Active Directory. So we'll start with the first command, which is to install the dependencies.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:58.320
Once that's complete, we can go ahead and join the realm. Something that's a little bit different

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:07.440
from the documentation to the command that we're using here is the membership software flag.

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:15.599
Because the Active Directory is on the latest version of Windows, Windows 2025, or rather

00:01:15.599 --> 00:01:23.120
Microsoft Server 2025, it doesn't want to connect unless we have the membership software set as

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:29.599
Samba and there are a few open issues about that on Microsoft communities, but we're going to use

00:01:29.599 --> 00:01:36.559
that command which will prompt us for a password and the password we can enter it in there.

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:44.800
And if that works, you'll see successfully enrolled machine in realm and you can do a realm list

00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:50.160
just to check that you're enrolled in the correct realm if you have multiple Active Directory hosts.

00:01:50.959 --> 00:01:57.599
So you can see the realm name there. In this case, it's posit.co. And if you'd like to verify one of

00:01:57.599 --> 00:02:08.720
your users, you can ID them. And if this works, you know you're connected to the right realm.

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:15.600
So if we ID the user, we can see that this user is and all the groups that they're part of.

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:21.679
So now that you're connected to the realm, that connects your Linux server to the

00:02:23.039 --> 00:02:28.880
Active Directory. Now we need to point Workbench to start using your Active Directory

00:02:29.679 --> 00:02:33.679
credentials. So we can copy the login PAM profile.

00:02:35.600 --> 00:02:44.320
And we're going to be using PAM with SSSD today to configure this. So now if we go to

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:52.320
we need to open up a file and make an addition to automatically create home directories.

00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:56.240
You can manually create them as well, but in most cases, creating them

00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:05.600
automatically is a little bit easier. So that's in the etcpam.d common session file.

00:03:09.919 --> 00:03:17.679
And we'll scroll down to session required PAM underscore unix.so.

00:03:17.919 --> 00:03:24.479
And you can paste this in. This is also mentioned in our official documentation,

00:03:24.479 --> 00:03:29.039
so you can refer to that if you want to get the exact line.

00:03:32.240 --> 00:03:34.240
So once that's done, we can save that.

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:45.199
And one more thing that in most cases you won't need to do, but in for this demo,

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:52.320
we don't have any group policies set on the Active Directory. So what we have to do is

00:03:52.960 --> 00:04:00.559
we have to make an adjustment to our sssd.conf because otherwise we won't be able to log in.

00:04:00.559 --> 00:04:07.279
We effectively need to set all group policies so that they're not enforced when we try to log in.

00:04:07.279 --> 00:04:13.039
Otherwise, that will block us. So run this command.

00:04:13.279 --> 00:04:18.559
You may not need to run this, but I would suggest consulting your IT team if you

00:04:19.119 --> 00:04:23.920
would like to, if you need this command or whether you don't.

